Drunk on corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place drunk.
Therefore, I suggested that he not drive.
He asked me why.
"You drank," I said to him, "don't you fear the police?"
Boris replied: "No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin's image, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a policeman who wasn't corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to get into the traffic police force, you have to buy your chief's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things the right way drown in bureaucratic red tape.
"By paying 100 dollars, you can drive in the city without brakes!"
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes everywhere and for everything.
According to Boris, the only ones who don't accept it are those to whom it isn't offered.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officials, and even the Kremlin: no one is immune anywhere.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such poor taste, I asked who owned them and heard in response that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most appealing property belonged to a modest tax office employee.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, bureaucrats, and police who sold weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that transported 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka Theatre siege, where many victims died during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A bus passenger covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from smelling them.
A very unnecessary precaution.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same thing.
A policeman came to ask him, "do you know the price?" and the driver replied, "of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, amounting to entire days for the journey.
The war against Chechnya goes on endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al-Qaeda and the entire "international terrorist network," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves—who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their possessions—sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating where the minefields are, and supply the rebels with forged documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gunsmith shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels, on the other hand, have ammunition supplies, from which weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this scourge.
Punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No officials want to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called "simple people" view this phenomenon with goodwill.
They say about their mayor, "Of course he's corrupt, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, you can travel for 50 rubles.
Both the traveler and the conductor benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on board the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you do not want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, run red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to take the blame for the police.
Alexander Menchikov, Peter the Great's minister, had understood the impossibility of winning the struggle against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since then, the situation has worsened.
Getting rid of corruption might well leave the state without citizens, but if the spread of corruption is not stopped, citizens will soon be left without a state.
